  "target_response": {
    "text": "Electrolytes are a real thing, not bro-science — sodium is the main mineral you lose in sweat, and on hot runs lasting past about 90 minutes, replacing some of it helps you absorb fluid and avoid that depleted, crampy feeling late in the run. For a session like yesterday's 95-minute run in the heat, a standard electrolyte tab or sports drink would have been a perfectly reasonable call. The practical version: drink to thirst rather than to a rigid schedule, add electrolytes on the long hot sessions, and skip them for short easy runs where plain water is plenty. If you notice white salt residue on your skin or kit afterwards, you're a saltier sweater and they'll matter a bit sooner. One caveat: if you take blood-pressure medication or follow a sodium-restricted diet, check with your doctor first.",
